Hi there,

Dnia czwartek, 13 marca 2014 09:59:24 John Young pisze:
> (...)
> Freedom of comsec, say, as a new entry in the US Bill of Rights
> could lead the way for it to be a fundamental element of Human
> Rights.

You had me up until this part.

We don't need it. We have the secrecy of correspondence in most democra=
tic=20
countries:
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secrecy_of_correspondence

Well, the US kind of needs to get it into the Bill of Rights, maybe, bu=
t not=20
as "comsec", but as plain old "secrecy of correspondence".

Why? Because instead of creating a new "cyber"/"comsec" right, it's hig=
h time=20
we uphold the rights we already have. Otherwise, once a new technology =
comes,=20
we will have to fight this fight all over again -- as this will no long=
er be=20
"comsec", but (say) "quantumsec".

Again, where we have secrecy of correspondence already -- let's enforce=
 it;=20
where it is not there, it needs to be implemented and enshrined in law.=
 But=20
only as a general rule of "secrecy of correspondence", not as "comsec",=
 not as=20
"postal secrecy", not as "telephone privacy", as otherwise we will have=
 the=20
same discussion in 5-10 years all over again.

=2D-=20
Pozdr
rysiek
